  "prompt": "What is if statement?",
  "response": "An **if statement** is a fundamental control structure in programming that allows you to execute a block of code conditionally based on whether a specified condition is true or false. It is one of the most basic ways to make decisions in a program.\n\n### Syntax (general form):\n```python\nif condition:\n    # Code to execute if the condition is true\n```\n\n### How it works:\n1. The **condition** is evaluated. This is typically a boolean expression (e.g., `x > 5`).\n2. If the condition is `True`, the block of code inside the `if` statement is executed.\n3. If the condition is `False`, the block of code is skipped, and the program continues with the next statement after the `if` block.\n\n### Example in Python:\n```python\nx = 10\nif x > 5:\n    print(\"x is greater than 5\")\n```\nOutput:\n```\nx is greater than 5\n```\n\n### Extensions of `if` statements:\n1. **`else` statement**:\n   Used to execute a block of code when the `if` condition is `False`.\n   ```python\n   if x > 5:\n       print(\"x is greater than 5\")\n   else:\n       print(\"x is less than or equal to 5\")\n   ```\n\n2. **`elif` statement** (else if):\n   Used to check multiple conditions sequentially.\n   ```python\n   if x > 10:\n       print(\"x is greater than 10\")\n   elif x == 10:\n       print(\"x is equal to 10\")\n   else:\n       print(\"x is less than 10\")\n   ```\n\n### Key Points:\n- The `if` statement is essential for implementing decision-making logic in programs.\n- Conditions must evaluate to a boolean value (`True` or `False`).\n- Proper indentation is crucial in languages like Python to define the block of code associated with the `if` statement.",
